The article discusses the Let Girls Learn initiative, which aims to provide adolescent girls around the world with a quality education. The initiative takes a comprehensive approach, addressing health, economic, and societal barriers that girls face. The US government has invested over $1 billion in programming in more than 50 countries and has established partnerships with private sector organizations. The article also highlights the barriers to girls' education, such as gender norms, violence, and early marriage. The initiative focuses on coordinated government action, diplomacy, raising awareness, and partnerships to achieve its goals. The US government agencies involved include the Department of State, USAID, Peace Corps, Millennium Challenge Corporation, Department of Labor, and Department of Agriculture. The article emphasizes the importance of girls' education in achieving sustainable development goals and gender equality.